# Difference Between `==` and `.equals()` in Java

## 1. `==` Operator

### Description
- Compares **memory reference (address)**
- Checks whether two objects point to the same location in memory
- For **primitive types**, it compares actual values

### Example with Primitives
```java
int a = 10;
int b = 10;

System.out.println(a == b);   // true (values are equal)
```

### Example with Objects
```java
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = new String("Java");

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // false (different memory locations)
```

> ⚠️ **Note:** Even though the content is the same, these objects are different because they exist at different memory addresses.

---

## 2. `.equals()` Method

### Description
- Compares **content/value** of objects
- Defined in the `Object` class
- Many classes like `String`, `Integer`, `ArrayList` override it for custom comparison logic

### Example
```java
String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = new String("Java");

System.out.println(s1.equals(s2));   // true (content is equal)
```

---

## 3. Special Case: String Literals

When using String literals (not the `new` keyword), Java uses the **String Pool**:

```java
String s1 = "Java";
String s2 = "Java";

System.out.println(s1 == s2);   // true (both point to same location in String Pool)
```

> 💡 **Why?** String literals are stored in a special memory region called the **String Pool**, so both variables reference the same object.

---

## Quick Comparison Table

| Feature | `==` | `.equals()` |
|---------|------|-----------|
| **Compares** | Memory reference | Content/Value |
| **For Primitives** | Compares values | N/A |
| **For Objects** | Compares memory address | Compares content |
| **Overridable** | No | Yes |
| **Default behavior** | Reference equality | Defined by class |